(Baker)
</taxonomicName>
: 
<treatmentCitation id="0AB0E10CFF8FFF8BFE6AFDCDFD20FDF2" author="" box="[497,739,577,599]" page="265" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<bibRefCitation id="EF80BAECFF8FFF8BFE6AFDCDFD71FDF2" box="[497,690,577,599]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" refId="ref5380" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. (1992) Oriental nirvanine leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: a review of C. F. Baker's species and keys to the genera and species from Singapore, Borneo and the Philippines. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 249 - 273." type="journal article">Viraktamath, 1992</bibRefCitation>
: 265
</treatmentCitation>
, figs.112–117.
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAEC71DFF8FFF8BFF0CFD08FEEBFCAD" blockId="4.[151,1437,644,1029]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Crown with paired small reddish spots joined at midline at apex, one median and two lateral stripes continued onto pronotum, orange. In some males, posterior half of pronotum orange, median stripe continued onto scutellum. Forewing with three fuscous oblique stripes on coastal area in apical half of forewing, black spot when present very tiny dot-like.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30B9496FF8FFF8BFF5CFC98FA84FCF5" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BAEC71DFF8FFF8BFF5CFC98FA84FCF5" blockId="4.[151,1437,644,1029]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9651B0FFF8FFF8BFF5CFC98FEB1FC89" box="[199,370,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
As described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF80BAECFF8FFF8BFDA9FC98FCCCFC89" box="[562,783,788,813]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" refId="ref5380" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. (1992) Oriental nirvanine leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: a review of C. F. Baker's species and keys to the genera and species from Singapore, Borneo and the Philippines. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 249 - 273." type="journal article">Viraktamath (1992)</bibRefCitation>
, but with the following additional features. Aedeagus with apex of shaft strongly anteriorly curved, apex membranous, processes of the aedeagus some times unequal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
